<DocsLayout title="Subdomain Tracking - Infinity Metrics">
  <h1>Subdomain Tracking</h1>
  <p>
    Track visitors across multiple subdomains as a single website to get a
    complete picture of user behavior.
  </p>

  <h2>Enable Subdomain Tracking</h2>
  <p>Configure Infinity Metrics to track across subdomains:</p>
  <pre><code>Infinity.init(&#123;
  site_id: 'your-site-id',
  track_subdomains: true,
  cookie_domain: '.example.com'
&#125;);</code></pre>

  <h2>How It Works</h2>
  <p>When subdomain tracking is enabled:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Visitors are tracked across all subdomains</li>
    <li>Sessions persist when navigating between subdomains</li>
    <li>Referrers between subdomains are handled correctly</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Configuration Options</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>track_subdomains</strong> - Enable/disable subdomain tracking
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>cookie_domain</strong> - Domain for session cookies (use leading dot)
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>include_subdomains</strong> - Array of specific subdomains to track
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Examples</h2>
  <p>Track across blog.example.com, shop.example.com, and example.com:</p>
  <pre><code>Infinity.init(&#123;
  site_id: 'your-site-id',
  track_subdomains: true,
  cookie_domain: '.example.com'
&#125;);</code></pre>

  <p>Next: <a href="/docs/administration">Administration</a></p>
</DocsLayout>
